column2: The Arabyans value life and endeavour in the noble pursuit of healing and easing suffering.
The garrison-port was established long ago under the orders of the then Phoenix King Morvael. The looming towers still serve as a reminder of the Asur's colonial might.
As part of the Pactsworn, the Skaven and Rotbloods combine their forces to bring ruin to their enemies.
As the Skaven are allowed to burrow deeper and wider they bring with them the rank and file.
As the Pactsworn bears its rotten fruits the Rottblood can now bring to bear the fiercest of Skaven.
Like most races, those from Albion are no stranger to felling trees to use in construction.
Most Albion architecture is based around mud buildings with thatched roofing with wood reserved for their more grandiose buildings.
With a glut of wood available, common log cabins can be seen sprouting up amongst the common folk.
Albion lacks the technology to properly mine, so with crude pickaxes they work on above-ground seams of gold.
Albion lacks the technology to properly mine, so with crude pickaxes they work on above-ground seams of gold.
Albion lacks the technology to properly mine, so with crude pickaxes they work on above-ground seams of gold.
The wise elderly women of Albion, who know the old ways forage for herbs which will cure all manner of ills.
No one can afford to ignore a plentiful, cheap source of food from the waters nearby.
A deep-sea fishing fleet can bring in a larger catch than inshore boats. Most of the catch has to be salted or pickled for return to port.
A major fishery is a complex network of workshops and small industries, all providing the support needed for large scale fishing.
Truthsaysers are masters of honing out trinkets of interest.
Artifacts lost to time need special care to bring them back to their former power and splendor.
The Ogham Stones hold immense power and by extension the druids that protect and maintain them.
Here knights are drilled with a blend of traditional swordsmanship and unusual techniques birthed in Lahmia dating back to the ancient days of the Harkoni tribe.
Halflings scoff at the old slingshots they called catapults, now they are replaced by the real thing.
A workshop to tinker with their prized possession and maybe fashion a few catapults.

Soup, soup, a tasty soup, soup, a spicy carrot and coriander (Chilli chowder). Crouton, crouton, crunchy friends in a liquid broth, I am gazpacho, Oh, I am a summer soup â€“ Traditional Halfling Folk Song
While soup is arguably the most popular Halfling dish, pies baked in a buttery crispy crust... buttery flavoured crust, flaky I mean flaky crust is a very close second.
A place of food galore and pints of beer, that's right, it comes in pints.
Small tobacco plots dot the land, their owners keep most of the crop while selling any excess at the local markets.
Larger in production, tobacco farms are able to cater to the townsfolk who live in the towns across the Moot including its capital Eicheschatten.

Large scale tobacco cultivation uses large swathes of land damaging local countryside. Through economy of scales they are able to service all of the Empire and beyond, making tobacco a lucrative cash crop.
The Halflings have always been attuned with nature but to shy away from industry and embrace the land is truly a wonderful sight.
Halflings have long cultivated tobacco, producing the finest tobaccy throughout the Old World. Gipfel is very much at the heart of this burgeoning industry.
Great knowledge and many riches can be gained from the ancient Nehekharan King's tombs.
Fierce norscan tribesmen pour out in droves harkening their Dark Masters call.
Fimir are no strangers to tearing the fabric of the mortal realm in order to summon demons to their cause.
Only the brave, foolish or a demon themselves would create a portal of this magnitude to the depths of the Chaos Wastes.
To see the end times one must merely gaze through the abyss.
Unearthed these Waystones are nothing more than ruins covered in moss and tainted by chaos.
As the Waystones are slowly repaired Chaos is drained from the world and offers protection to Albion.
The waystones surge with power and with it the attention of evil beings.
A Waystone Marker helps Druids focus and calibrate the Albion Waystones allowing them to work more effectively.
Using a shard from the Albion Waystones the druids are able to construct a beacon that can feed from Waystones power even at a great distance, though at the loss of some power.
Pigs under halfling care grow so fat and hearty that in dire times they can be ridden into battle. Some muse the pigs fight with such unexpected fury as only to avoid the plate.
Warhorses are far too unwieldy to a halfling and ponies too gentle. As such specially trained cockerels are reared for the halflings to charge into war on.

Tricksy little halflings snatch the eggs and are long gone before the mother even realises. As they tumble down the mountains with their prize, her shrieks and wails can be heard across the mountain tops. This trade has it detractors who see it as a cruel practice.

Giant Trolls are usually avoided by their smaller kin and have plenty of room for themselves. The messy leftovers of their meals often attract feral Wyverns which sometimes will follow the trolls around in the hope of more easy prey.

In this unremarkable Isle, a series of great, grassy mounds dot the landscape. Ancient man-made hills, serving as the burial tombs of mighty kings and warriors who will rise uneasily to face intruders.
Even the tribes of Albion can't resist the Dark Emissaries honeyed words of power and riches that emanate from the black citadel.
The citadel is rebuilt anew, a strange and baroque structure of twisted spires and warped gates, that can darken even the most noble soul.
They meet in the dead of night, Nurgle cultists and fanatics to make sacrifice and offer their thanks for the Fly Fathers rotten gifts.
Old forts twisted and warped to their new decaying masters designs. Most beings know to stay clear unless they wish to seek out the rot or end up in a cauldron as part of an unholy feast.
A foreboding sight, it resembles little of it's former structure, even to look at it's mad and impossible architecture is to risk insanity.

Lights shine from it's many turrets, a glow that drains life from the landscape instead of illuminating it. Sharpened spikes litter the walls ready to implale any who dare scale it. Flee from this place if you value your soul.
